const blogContent = `
<p>The primary challenge in developing autonomous mathematical research agents is ensuring rigorous grounding. Without a formal verification loop, large language models (LLMs) tend to generate plausible but logically ungrounded conjectures.</p>

<p>Our initial pipeline demonstrated significant heuristic capability but lacked structural constraints. The Architect (our central hub) could generate structurally complete research outlines—including citations and abstracts—that were nevertheless hallucinatory. To contribute to actual mathematical literature, we moved to a Hub-and-Spoke architecture that enforces strict evidentiary requirements.</p>

<h2>Grounding via the Librarian Spoke</h2>

<p>The solution involves a strict Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) framework. The Architect is interfaced with the <strong>Librarian</strong>, a specialized spoke powered by a local LanceDB vector store containing a curated subset of the arXiv corpus.</p>

<p>The workflow follows a deterministic protocol:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Query Execution</strong>: The Librarian embeds the research query and retrieves the most relevant peer-reviewed literature.</li>
  <li><strong>Stochastic Sampling</strong>: Relevant documents are sampled to provide diverse starting points for parallel research branches.</li>
  <li><strong>Contextual Injecton</strong>: The Architect's prompt is constrained by the retrieved paper's title, arXiv ID, and abstract. The model is directed to base its analysis strictly on the provided context, operating at a low temperature (0.1) to prioritize precision over creative variance.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Falsification and the Explorer Spoke</h2>

<p>Once grounded, the system can investigate specific claims. For instance, when analyzing literature on random graphs (e.g., arXiv:1903.10570), the Architect hypothesized specific fluctuation regimes for the $p = 1/\\sqrt{n}$ critical density limit in 4-cycles ($C_4$).</p>

<p>The <strong>Explorer</strong> spoke then executed a battery of empirical tests—utilizing Python-based computational statistics and random matrix theory—to test the hypothesis. In this instance, the quantitative predictions were found to be empirically flawed at scale.</p>

<p>This empirical feedback is critical. While LLMs struggle with general infinite limits, we utilize a <strong>Computational Fast-Path</strong>: the system targets <em>finite, computable failing bounds</em>. These counterexamples are then passed to the Lean 4 formalization spoke.</p>

<p>Following the empirical failure, the system generated a Lean 4 theorem to formalize the boundary condition:</p>

<pre><code class="language-lean">theorem c4_variance_falsification_N64 :
  let n : ℕ := 64 in
  let p : ℚ := 1 / 8 in
  variance_subgraph_count (cycle_graph 4) n (fun (_ _ : Fin 64) => p) &gt; (n ^ 3 : ℚ) / 2
</code></pre>

<p>By targeting $N = 64$ and $p = 1/8$ (where $1/\\sqrt{64} = 1/8$), the system reduced a complex asymptotic question to a finite, decidable computation. The Lean 4 kernel then leveraged <code>native_decide</code> and <code>norm_num</code> to verify the falsification.</p>

<h2>Verification and the Red Team</h2>

<p>In our Hub-and-Spoke model, the <strong>Red Team</strong> agent serves as a final verification spoke. When the Architect attempts to formalize findings, the Red Team subjects the candidate theorems to rigorous audit.</p>

<p>The Red Team's evaluation criteria include:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Counterexample Construction</strong>: Attempting to find specific mathematical objects that violate the conjecture.</li>
  <li><strong>Novelty Detection</strong>: Comparing the bound against known results (e.g., standard applications of Cauchy-Schwarz).</li>
  <li><strong>Scope Validation</strong>: Ensuring the formal statement does not overreach the empirical evidence.</li>
</ul>

<p>This multi-agent verification ensures that the pipeline only produces outputs that are novel, formally verified, and properly scoped.</p>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>

<p>Perqed operates as a neuro-symbolic pipeline applying a formalized version of the scientific method. By integrating live literature retrieval, empirical testing, and formal verification into a Hub-and-Spoke architecture, we move beyond simple text generation toward verifiable mathematical discovery.</p>
`;
